<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-260-887  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 260 887.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  Jan 16 1989 n400 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MAI Basic Four poised to seize Prime's reins. (Prime ComputerInc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lazar, Jerry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>MAI Basic Four (MBF) is on the verge of succeeding in its$20-per-share hostile takeover of Prime Computer.andP;  MBF hasgarnered 29.3 million shares tendered from Prime shareholders toadd to the two million shares MBF owns outright.andP;  MBF now needattain only another 1 million shares, less than three percent ofthe 48.5 million shares still outstanding, to reach the 67 percentvoting majority needed for the takeover.andP;  Prime's last good chanceto stave off MBF rests with US District Court Judge David Mazzone,who will rule on Prime's allegations that MBF is improperlyfinancing the deal by securing the purchase with over 50 percentof Prime's outstanding stock, which would be in violation of SECregulations on margin purchases.andP;  Another factor is Prime's $375million in 5.75-percent interest-bearing outstanding convertibledebentures; if they were all exercised, MBF's stock holdings inPrime would be diluted to 48 percent.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   MAI Basic Four Inc. (acquisitions and mergers)Prime Computer Inc. (acquisitions and mergers).andO;Ticker:    MBF; PRM.andO;Topic:     AcquisitionComputer IndustryTakeovers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>